D&D Ranger Class Features:

Class Features
As a ranger, you gain the following class features.
Hit Points:
Hit Dice: 1d10 per ranger level
Hit Points at 1st Level: 10 + your Constitution modifier
Hit Points at Higher Levels: 1d10 (or 6) + your Constitution modifier per ranger level after 1st

Proficiencies:
Armor: Light armor, medium armor, shields
Weapons: Simple weapons, martial weapons
Tools: None
Saving Throws: Strength, Dexterity
Skills: Choose three from Animal Handling, Athletics, Insight, Investigation, Nature, Perception, Stealth, and Survival

Flashcards:

{"term": "What is a Ranger?", "definition": "A character class in tabletop role-playing games that specializes in wilderness survival and combat."}
{"term": "What are Hit Points?", "definition": "A measure of a character's health and durability in the game, determined by hit dice and Constitution modifier. (10 + Constitution modifier at first level)"}
{"term": "What are a Ranger’s Hit Dice?", "definition": "The type of dice used to determine hit points for a ranger (1d10 per ranger level)."}
{"term": "What are Proficiencies?", "definition": "Skills and abilities that rangers are trained in, including armor, weapons, saving throws, and skills."}
{"term": "What are a Ranger’s Armor Proficiencies?", "definition": "Rangers are proficient in light armor, medium armor, and shields."}
{"term": "What are a Ranger’s Weapon Proficiencies?", "definition": "Rangers are proficient in simple weapons and martial weapons."}
{"term": "What are the Ranger’s Saving Throws Proficiencies?", "definition": "Rangers have proficiency in saving throws for Strength and Dexterity."}
{"term": "What can be a Ranger’s Skills Proficiencies?", "definition": "Rangers can choose three skills from a list including Animal Handling, Athletics, Insight, Investigation, Nature, Perception, Stealth, and Survival."}

Description of OpenGL from learnopengl.com:
OpenGL is mainly considered an API (an Application Programming Interface) that provides us with a large set of functions that we can use to manipulate graphics and images. However, OpenGL by itself is not an API, but merely a specification, developed and maintained by the Khronos Group.

The OpenGL specification specifies exactly what the result/output of each function should be and how it should perform. It is then up to the developers implementing this specification to come up with a solution of how this function should operate. Since the OpenGL specification does not give us implementation details, the actual developed versions of OpenGL are allowed to have different implementations, as long as their results comply with the specification (and are thus the same to the user).

The people developing the actual OpenGL libraries are usually the graphics card manufacturers. Each graphics card that you buy supports specific versions of OpenGL which are the versions of OpenGL developed specifically for that card (series). When using an Apple system the OpenGL library is maintained by Apple themselves and under Linux there exists a combination of graphic suppliers' versions and hobbyists' adaptations of these libraries. This also means that whenever OpenGL is showing weird behavior that it shouldn't, this is most likely the fault of the graphics cards manufacturers (or whoever developed/maintained the library).
Since most implementations are built by graphics card manufacturers, whenever there is a bug in the implementation this is usually solved by updating your video card drivers; those drivers include the newest versions of OpenGL that your card supports. This is one of the reasons why it's always advised to occasionally update your graphic drivers.

Khronos publicly hosts all specification documents for all the OpenGL versions. The interested reader can find the OpenGL specification of version 3.3 (which is what we'll be using) here which is a good read if you want to delve into the details of OpenGL (note how they mostly just describe results and not implementations). The specifications also provide a great reference for finding the exact workings of its functions.

Flashcards:

{"term": "What is OpenGL?", "definition": "OpenGL is a specification for a graphics API (Application Programming Interface) that provides functions for manipulating graphics and images."}
{"term": "Who is the Khronos Group?", "definition": "The organization responsible for developing and maintaining the OpenGL specification."}
{"term": "OpenGL Implementation", "definition": "The actual software libraries and drivers developed by graphics card manufacturers or other entities to implement the OpenGL specification on specific hardware."}
{"term": "What are Graphics Card Manufacturers?", "definition": "Companies that produce graphics cards and develop OpenGL implementations for their hardware."}
{"term": "What can Updating Video Card Drivers do?", "definition": "A recommended action to fix issues with OpenGL implementations, as newer drivers often include bug fixes and support for the latest OpenGL versions."}
{"term": "What is an OpenGL Specification?", "definition": "A document specifying how OpenGL functions should behave and the results they should produce, without providing implementation details."}

From https://blog.hubspot.com/sales/accounting-101 (an Accounting 101 site):
Accounting is something that most people have heard about at work, on TV, or online. But that doesn't mean you really get the basics of accounting. Like many careers, accounting is a mix of tactical and analytical tasks. And it's not just recording transactions or doing taxes. Accounting is thinking about what your financial records will mean to regulators, agencies, and tax collectors. If you're in charge of accounting, it's not just numbers and receipts. It's a process of gathering and reporting financial information. You'll use those reports to communicate the cash flows, financial position, and performance of your business. Understanding accounting often begins with learning basic terms and principles. These can help you learn the foundation of accounting. Then, it's about learning how you can apply these practices. But before we dig into those ideas, let's talk about what day-to-day work looks like for an accountant.

What do accountants do every day?
Accountants oversee the financial records for a business and make sure the data is correct. Then, they use this data to create budgets, financial documents, and reports. Examples of this might include a cash flow statement for operations or an income statement for an upcoming board meeting.

They also attend meetings to offer advice or look into legal issues. Other common activities include:
	Collecting new financial data
	Reviewing or updating past records
	Collecting evidence for audits and other legal proceedings
	Computing taxes
	Checking on compliance with relevant laws
	Making sure tax payments are on time
	Forecasting and risk-assessment

Flashcards:
{"term": "What is Accounting?", "definition": "The practice of recording, organizing, and reporting financial information for businesses and individuals."}
{"term": "What are Financial Records?", "definition": "Documents that track financial transactions and activities within a business or organization."}
{"term": "Who are Regulators?", "definition": "Government or industry authorities responsible for overseeing and enforcing financial rules and regulations."}
{"term": "What are Cash Flows?", "definition": "The movement of money in and out of a business, which accountants analyze and report."}
{"term": "What is Financial Performance?", "definition": "Refers to how well a business is doing financially, often assessed through income statements and other financial reports."}
{"term": "What are an Accountant's Daily Tasks?", "definition": "The responsibilities of accountants, including overseeing financial records, creating budgets, preparing financial documents, attending meetings, collecting and reviewing data, ensuring compliance with laws, and forecasting."}
{"term": "What are Audits?", "definition": "Examinations of financial records to ensure accuracy and compliance with regulations."}
{"term": "Forecasting and Risk Assessment", "definition": "Evaluating future financial trends and potential risks to help businesses make informed decisions."}

Vaccines + Autism:
Vaccines do not cause autism.

	Some people have had concerns that ASD might be linked to the vaccines children receive, but studies have shown that there is no link between receiving vaccines and developing ASD. The National Academy of Medicine, formerly known as Institute of Medicine, reviewed the safety of 8 vaccines to children and adults. The review found that with rare exceptions, these vaccines are very safe

	A CDC study published in 2013 added to the research showing that vaccines do not cause ASD. The study focused on the number of antigens given during the first two years of life. Antigens are substances in vaccines that cause the body’s immune system to produce disease-fighting antibodies. The results showed that the total amount of antigen from vaccines received was the same between children with ASD and those that did not have ASD.

One vaccine ingredient that has been studied specifically is thimerosal. Thimerosal is a mercury-based preservative used to prevent germs (like bacteria and fungi) from contaminating multidose vials of vaccines. Research shows that thimerosal does not cause ASD. In fact, a 2004 scientific review by the IOM concluded that “the evidence favors rejection of a causal relationship between thimerosal–containing vaccines and autism.”

Since 2003, there have been nine CDC-funded or conducted studies that have found no link between thimerosal-containing vaccines and ASD. These studies also found no link between the measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) vaccine and ASD in children.

Flashcards:
{"term": "Link between Vaccines and Autism", "definition": "The idea that vaccines may cause Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD), which has been scientifically disproven."}
{"term": "ASD (Autism Spectrum Disorder)", "definition": "A developmental disorder characterized by challenges in social interaction and communication, with a range of symptoms and severity."}
{"term": "National Academy of Medicine", "definition": "An institution that reviewed the safety of vaccines and concluded that, with rare exceptions, vaccines are very safe."}
{"term": "What is the CDC?", "definition": "A U.S. government agency, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, that conducted studies confirming that vaccines do not cause ASD."}
{"term": "What are Antigens?", "definition": "Substances in vaccines that stimulate the immune system to produce antibodies and fight diseases."}
{"term": "What is Thimerosal?", "definition": "A mercury-based preservative used in vaccines to prevent contamination; research has shown it does not cause ASD."}
{"term": "What is the IOM?", "definition": "A scientific institution, the Institute of Medicine, that reviewed and concluded that there is no causal relationship between thimerosal-containing vaccines and autism."}
{"term": "What is an MMR Vaccine?", "definition": "Measles, mumps, and rubella vaccine; studies have found no link between the MMR vaccine and ASD in children."}

Model Penal Code (from Cornell Law):
The Model Penal Code (or MPC) is a model code assembled by the American Legal Institute that was first promulgated in 1962. Following the MPC’s promulgation, many states’ criminal codes underwent significant reforms, and to this day, many states’ criminal codes are based on the MPC.

The MPC is comprised of four parts: (I) general principles of liability; (II) definitions of specific offenses; (III) provisions governing treatment and correction; and (IV) provisions governing the organization of corrections departments and divisions.

Two of the MPC’s parts have gained historic significance: (I) the general principles of liability and (II) the definition of specific offenses. The sentencing, treatment, and corrections portions of parts III and IV were not as well-received and were quickly left behind.

The MPC defined crimes using an elements analysis to distinguish between the different elements of a crime that are required for liability. Additionally, the MPC standardized mens rea terms to determine defendants’ mental states.

Flashcards:
{"term": "Define Model Penal Code (MPC)", "definition": "A model code created by the American Law Institute in 1962, serving as a template for state criminal codes and leading to significant criminal law reforms in various states."}
{"term": "What are General Principles of Liability?", "definition": "Part I of the MPC, which outlines fundamental concepts of criminal liability."}
{"term": "What are Definitions of Specific Offenses?", "definition": "Part II of the MPC, which provides detailed definitions of specific criminal offenses."}
{"term": "What are Treatment and Correction Provisions?", "definition": "Part III of the MPC, covering aspects related to the treatment and correction of offenders."}
{"term": "What is the Organization of Corrections Departments?", "definition": "Part IV of the MPC, dealing with the structure and organization of corrections departments and divisions."}
{"term": "What is an Elements Analysis?", "definition": "A method used by the MPC to break down crimes into their essential elements necessary for establishing liability."}
{"term": "Define Mens Rea", "definition": "The mental state of a defendant, which the MPC standardized in its definitions of offenses, helping to determine culpability."}
